Bank Churn Prediction¶

Objective:¶

Given a Bank customer, build a neural network-based classifier that can determine whether they will leave or not in the next 6 months.

Context:¶

Businesses like banks that provide service have to worry about the problem of 'Churn' i.e. customers leaving and joining another service provider. It is important to understand which aspects of the service influence a customer's decision in this regard. Management can concentrate efforts on the improvement of service, keeping in mind these priorities.

Data Description:¶

The case study is from an open-source dataset from Kaggle. The dataset contains 10,000 sample points with 14 distinct features such as CustomerId, CreditScore, Geography, Gender, Age, Tenure, Balance, etc. Link to the Kaggle project site:https://www.kaggle.com/barelydedicated/bank-customer-churn-modeling

Observation:¶

  • CreditScore has the outliers on the left side, is negatively skewed with distribution ranging from 350 to 850
  • Geography has the maximum distribution for France and then for Germany and Spain
  • Gender has maximum distribuition for Males
  • Age has outliers on the right side, is positively skewed with distribution ranging from 18 to 92
  • Tenure is ranging from 0 to 10, with Max distrubtion for 2 and least for 0 tenure
  • Balance has no outliers, is negatively skewed, It ranges from 0 to 250898.09, with max distribution for 0
  • NoOfProducts is categorical, values ranging from 0 to 4, with max distribution for 0
  • HasCrCard is categorical, values ranging from 0 to 1, with Max people with Credit Card
  • IsActiveMember is categorical, values ranging from 0 to 1, with max distribution for 1(being Active)
  • EstimatedSalary has no outliers, with very slighty positively skewed. Distribution ranging from 11.58 to 199992.48
  • Exited is categorical, values ranging from 0 to 1, with max distribution for 0(being with bank)

In [87]:
# Initialize & build the model.
model = Sequential()

model.add(Dense(50, input_shape = (17,), activation = 'tanh'))
model.add(Dense(25, activation = 'tanh'))
model.add(Dense(10, activation = 'tanh'))
model.add(Dense(1, activation = 'sigmoid'))

model.compile(loss='binary_crossentropy',optimizer=optimizer, metrics=accuracy)

In [85]:
## function to get confusion matrix
def draw_cm(actual,predicted):
    cm = confusion_matrix(actual,predicted)
    sns.heatmap(cm,annot=True,fmt='.2f',xticklabels = [0,1] ,yticklabels = [0,1])
    plt.ylabel('Observed Exit Values')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted Exit Values')
    plt.show()
